stockmarket.stock

Interface OwnedStock

  • All Superinterfaces:
    Stock
    All Known Implementing Classes:
    DefaultOwnedStock

    public interface OwnedStock
extends Stock
    This interface extends the Stock interface with methods and fields defining a stock that is owned as part of a stock portfolio. This interface should be implemented either as a decorator class around a Stock implementation, or as a class that extends said Stock implementation.

    The main fields of this interface are the additional values for an owned stock. There will always be a quantity of shares owned, a principle (the initial amount spent on the shares), a total value of all shares combined, and a net which is the difference between the total value and the principle.

    Like the Stock interface, OwnedStock eschews direct setter methods. Instead, it inherits the setStockDetails() method from Stock, and brings two more methods, increaseShares() and decreaseShares(). The base properties of the stock are set by the inherited method, while the values of all the other fields are all dependent on the number of shares that are owned of the stock. Therefore increaseShares() and decreaseShares() should be implemented to change all values of this stock when they are called.

    Version:
    2.0
    Author:
    craig

        Parameters:

      • decreaseShares

        boolean decreaseShares(int quantity)
        Decrease the number of shares owned of this stok. Adjusts the principle, totalValue, and net based on the change. Returns a boolean value for whether or not there are any shares remaining of the stock.

        Code handling an instance of OwnedStock can use the boolean value it returns as a means of executing a special response to if all shares have been sold.

        Parameters:
        quantity - the quantity of shares to decrease by.
        Returns:
        true if there are shares remaining of the stock, false if there are not shares remaining.
